ch to net/core/sock.c ...<br />	cd /usr/src/linux/net/core<br />	patch -R &lt; xxx/reverse<br /><br />The only strange phase is the editing phase: you just want to remove <br />everything above the line that reads<br /><br />  diff -u --recursive --new-file v2.0.23/linux/net/core/sock.c linux/net/core/sock.c<br /><br />and then you want to remove everything that is after that patch (ie search<br />for the next line that starts with 'diff -u ..' and remove that and all<br />following lines). <br /><br />Does such a patched kernel result in full speed unix domain sockets again?  I<br />don't see anything else in the 2.0.24 patches that could even remotely result<br />in stuff like this.. (and the profiles weren't as conclusive as I hoped for)<br /><br />I'm leaving for two days in Norway in an hour, so I don't have the time <br />to check this out until I return late on Tuesday..<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
